265
0:10:50.26,000 --> 0:10:52,000
So these simple projections

266
0:10:52.26,000 --> 0:10:54,000
of the Goldman Sachs type

267
0:10:54.26,000 --> 0:10:56,000
are not telling us what we need to know

268
0:10:56.26,000 --> 0:10:57,000
about power transition.

269
0:10:57.26,000 --> 0:11:,000
But you might ask, well so what in any case?

270
0:11:00.26,000 --> 0:11:02,000
Why does it matter? Who cares?

271
0:11:02.26,000 --> 0:11:04,000
Is this just a game

272
0:11:04.26,000 --> 0:11:06,000
that diplomats and academics play?

273
0:11:06.26,000 --> 0:11:09,000
The answer is it matters quite a lot.

274
0:11:09.26,000 --> 0:11:11,000
Because, if you believe in decline

275
0:11:11.26,000 --> 0:11:14,000
and you get the answers wrong on this,

276
0:11:14.26,000 --> 0:11:16,000
the facts, not the myths,

277
0:11:16.26,000 --> 0:11:19,000
you may have policies which are very dangerous.

278
0:11:19.26,000 --> 0:11:22,000
Let me give you an example from history.

279
0:11:22.26,000 --> 0:11:24,000
The Peloponnesian War

280
0:11:24.26,000 --> 0:11:26,000
was the great conflict

281
0:11:26.26,000 --> 0:11:28,000
in which the Greek city state system

282
0:11:28.26,000 --> 0:11:31,000
tore itself apart

283
0:11:31.26,000 --> 0:11:34,000
two and a half millennia ago.

284
0:11:34.26,000 --> 0:11:36,000
What caused it?

285
0:11:36.26,000 --> 0:11:39,000
Thucydides, the great historian of the the Peloponnesian War,

286
0:11:39.26,000 --> 0:11:42,000
said it was the rise in the power of Athens

287
0:11:42.26,000 --> 0:11:45,000
and the fear it created in Sparta.

288
0:11:45.26,000 --> 0:11:48,000
Notice both halves of that explanation.

289
0:11:48.26,000 --> 0:11:5,000
Many people argue

290
0:11:50.26,000 --> 0:11:52,000
that the 21st century

291
0:11:52.26,000 --> 0:11:54,000
is going to repeat the 20th century,

292
0:11:54.26,000 --> 0:11:57,000
in which World War One,

293
0:11:57.26,000 --> 0:11:59,000
the great conflagration

294
0:11:59.26,000 --> 0:12:01,000
in which the European state system

295
0:12:01.26,000 --> 0:12:03,000
tore itself apart

296
0:12:03.26,000 --> 0:12:05,000
and destroyed its centrality in the world,

297
0:12:05.26,000 --> 0:12:07,000
that that was caused by

298
0:12:07.26,000 --> 0:12:09,000
the rise in the power of Germany

299
0:12:09.26,000 --> 0:12:12,000
and the fear it created in Britain.

300
0:12:12.26,000 --> 0:12:14,000
So there are people who are telling us

301
0:12:14.26,000 --> 0:12:16,000
this is going to be reproduced today,

302
0:12:16.26,000 --> 0:12:18,000
that what we're going to see

303
0:12:18.26,000 --> 0:12:21,000
is the same thing now in this century.

304
0:12:21.26,000 --> 0:12:23,000
No, I think that's wrong.

305
0:12:23.26,000 --> 0:12:25,000
It's bad history.

306
0:12:25.26,000 --> 0:12:27,000
For one thing, Germany had surpassed Britain

307
0:12:27.26,000 --> 0:12:29,000
in industrial strength by 1900.

308
0:12:29.26,000 --> 0:12:31,000
And as I said earlier,

309
0:12:31.26,000 --> 0:12:34,000
China has not passed the United States.

310
0:12:34.26,000 --> 0:12:36,000
But also, if you have this belief

311
0:12:36.26,000 --> 0:12:39,000
and it creates a sense of fear,

312
0:12:39.26,000 --> 0:12:41,000
it leads to overreaction.

313
0:12:41.26,000 --> 0:12:43,000
And the greatest danger we have

314
0:12:43.26,000 --> 0:12:46,000
of managing this power transition

315
0:12:46.26,000 --> 0:12:49,000
of the shift toward the East is fear.

316
0:12:49.26,000 --> 0:12:51,000
To paraphrase Franklin Roosevelt

317
0:12:51.26,000 --> 0:12:53,000
from a different context,

318
0:12:53.26,000 --> 0:12:56,000
the greatest thing we have to fear is fear itself.

319
0:12:56.26,000 --> 0:12:59,000
We don't have to fear the rise of China

320
0:12:59.26,000 --> 0:13:01,000
or the return of Asia.

321
0:13:01.26,000 --> 0:13:03,000
And if we have policies

322
0:13:03.26,000 --> 0:13:05,000
in which we take it

323
0:13:05.26,000 --> 0:13:07,000
in that larger historical perspective,

324
0:13:07.26,000 --> 0:13:09,000
we're going to be able

325
0:13:09.26,000 --> 0:13:11,000
to manage this process.

326
0:13:11.26,000 --> 0:13:13,000
Let me say a word now

327
0:13:13.26,000 --> 0:13:15,000
about the distribution of power

328
0:13:15.26,000 --> 0:13:18,000
and how it relates to power diffusion

329
0:13:18.26,000 --> 0:13:2,000
and then pull these two types together.

330
0:13:20.26,000 --> 0:13:23,000
If you ask how is power distributed in the world today,

331
0:13:23.26,000 --> 0:13:26,000
it's distributed much like

332
0:13:26.26,000 --> 0:13:29,000
a three-dimensional chess game.

333
0:13:29.26,000 --> 0:13:31,000
Top board:

334
0:13:31.26,000 --> 0:13:33,000
military power among states.

335
0:13:33.26,000 --> 0:13:36,000
The United States is the only superpower,

336
0:13:36.26,000 --> 0:13:38,000
and it's likely to remain that way

337
0:13:38.26,000 --> 0:13:4,000
for two or three decades.

338
0:13:40.26,000 --> 0:13:43,000
China's not going to replace the U.S. on this military board.

339
0:13:43.26,000 --> 0:13:46,000
Middle board of this three-dimensional chess game:

340
0:13:46.26,000 --> 0:13:48,000
economic power among states.

341
0:13:48.26,000 --> 0:13:51,000
Power is multi-polar.

342
0:13:51.26,000 --> 0:13:53,000
There are balancers --

343
0:13:53.26,000 --> 0:13:55,000
the U.S., Europe,

344
0:13:55.26,000 --> 0:13:57,000
China, Japan

345
0:13:57.26,000 --> 0:13:59,000
can balance each other.

346
0:13:59.26,000 --> 0:14:02,000
The bottom board of this three-dimensional,

347
0:14:02.26,000 --> 0:14:04,000
the board of transnational relations,

348
0:14:04.26,000 --> 0:14:07,000
things that cross borders outside the control of governments,

349
0:14:08.26,000 --> 0:14:11,000
things like climate change, drug trade,

350
0:14:11.26,000 --> 0:14:13,000
financial flows,

351
0:14:13.26,000 --> 0:14:15,000
pandemics,

352
0:14:15.26,000 --> 0:14:17,000
all these things that cross borders

353
0:14:17.26,000 --> 0:14:19,000
outside the control of governments,

354
0:14:19.26,000 --> 0:14:21,000
there nobody's in charge.

355
0:14:21.26,000 --> 0:14:23,000
It makes no sense to call this unipolar

356
0:14:23.26,000 --> 0:14:25,000
or multi-polar.

357
0:14:25.26,000 --> 0:14:27,000
Power is chaotically distributed.

358
0:14:27.26,000 --> 0:14:29,000
And the only way you can solve these problems --

359
0:14:29.26,000 --> 0:14:31,000
and this is where many greatest challenges

360
0:14:31.26,000 --> 0:14:33,000
are coming in this century --

361
0:14:33.26,000 --> 0:14:35,000
is through cooperation,

362
0:14:35.26,000 --> 0:14:37,000
through working together,

363
0:14:37.26,000 --> 0:14:4,000
which means that soft power becomes more important,

364
0:14:40.26,000 --> 0:14:42,000
that ability to organize networks

365
0:14:42.26,000 --> 0:14:44,000
to deal with these kinds of problems

366
0:14:44.26,000 --> 0:14:47,000
and to be able to get cooperation.

367
0:14:47.26,000 --> 0:14:49,000
Another way of putting it

368
0:14:49.26,000 --> 0:14:52,000
is that as we think of power in the 21st century,

369
0:14:52.26,000 --> 0:14:54,000
we want to get away from the idea

370
0:14:54.26,000 --> 0:14:56,000
that power's always zero sum --

371
0:14:56.26,000 --> 0:14:59,000
my gain is your loss and vice versa.

372
0:14:59.26,000 --> 0:15:02,000
Power can also be positive sum,

373
0:15:02.26,000 --> 0:15:05,000
where your gain can be my gain.

374
0:15:05.26,000 --> 0:15:08,000
If China develops greater energy security

375
0:15:08.26,000 --> 0:15:1,000
and greater capacity

376
0:15:10.26,000 --> 0:15:12,000
to deal with its problems of carbon emissions,

377
0:15:12.26,000 --> 0:15:14,000
that's good for us

378
0:15:14.26,000 --> 0:15:16,000
as well as good for China

379
0:15:16.26,000 --> 0:15:18,000
as well as good for everybody else.

380
0:15:18.26,000 --> 0:15:2,000
So empowering China

381
0:15:20.26,000 --> 0:15:23,000
to deal with its own problems of carbon

382
0:15:23.26,000 --> 0:15:26,000
is good for everybody,

383
0:15:26.26,000 --> 0:15:29,000
and it's not a zero sum, I win, you lose.

384
0:15:29.26,000 --> 0:15:31,000
It's one in which we can all gain.

385
0:15:31.26,000 --> 0:15:33,000
So as we think about power

386
0:15:33.26,000 --> 0:15:35,000
in this century,

387
0:15:35.26,000 --> 0:15:37,000
we want to get away from this view

388
0:15:37.26,000 --> 0:15:4,000
that it's all I win, you lose.

389
0:15:40.26,000 --> 0:15:43,000
Now I don't mean to be Pollyannaish about this.

390
0:15:43.26,000 --> 0:15:45,000
Wars persist. Power persists.

391
0:15:45.26,000 --> 0:15:47,000
Military power is important.

392
0:15:47.26,000 --> 0:15:49,000
Keeping balances is important.

393
0:15:49.26,000 --> 0:15:51,000
All this still persists.

394
0:15:51.26,000 --> 0:15:53,000
Hard power is there,

395
0:15:53.26,000 --> 0:15:55,000
and it will remain.

396
0:15:55.26,000 --> 0:15:57,000
But unless you learn how to mix

397
0:15:57.26,000 --> 0:15:59,000
hard power with soft power

398
0:15:59.26,000 --> 0:16:02,000
into strategies that I call smart power,

399
0:16:02.26,000 --> 0:16:04,000
you're not going to deal with the new kinds of problems

400
0:16:04.26,000 --> 0:16:07,000
that we're facing.

401
0:16:07.26,000 --> 0:16:1,000
So the key question that we need to think about as we look at this

402
0:16:10.26,000 --> 0:16:12,000
is how do we work together

403
0:16:12.26,000 --> 0:16:15,000
to produce global public goods,

404
0:16:15.26,000 --> 0:16:18,000
things from which all of us can benefit?

405
0:16:18.26,000 --> 0:16:2,000
How do we define our national interests

406
0:16:20.26,000 --> 0:16:22,000
so that it's not just zero sum,

407
0:16:22.26,000 --> 0:16:24,000
but positive sum.

408
0:16:24.26,000 --> 0:16:26,000
In that sense, if we define our interests,

409
0:16:26.26,000 --> 0:16:28,000
for example, for the United States

410
0:16:28.26,000 --> 0:16:31,000
the way Britain defined its interests in the 19th century,

411
0:16:31.26,000 --> 0:16:34,000
keeping an open trading system,

412
0:16:34.26,000 --> 0:16:37,000
keeping a monetary stability, keeping freedom of the seas --

413
0:16:37.26,000 --> 0:16:39,000
those were good for Britain,

414
0:16:39.26,000 --> 0:16:41,000
they were good for others as well.

415
0:16:41.26,000 --> 0:16:44,000
And in the 21st century, you have to do an analog to that.

416
0:16:44.26,000 --> 0:16:47,000
How do we produce global public goods,

417
0:16:47.26,000 --> 0:16:49,000
which are good for us,

418
0:16:49.26,000 --> 0:16:51,000
but good for everyone at the same time?

419
0:16:51.26,000 --> 0:16:53,000
And that's going to be the good news dimension

420
0:16:53.26,000 --> 0:16:55,000
of what we need to think about

421
0:16:55.26,000 --> 0:16:58,000
as we think of power in the 21st century.

422
0:16:58.26,000 --> 0:17:01,000
There are ways to define our interests

423
0:17:01.26,000 --> 0:17:04,000
in which, while protecting ourselves with hard power,

424
0:17:04.26,000 --> 0:17:07,000
we can organize with others in networks

425
0:17:07.26,000 --> 0:17:1,000
to produce, not only public goods,

426
0:17:10.26,000 --> 0:17:13,000
but ways that will enhance our soft power.

427
0:17:13.26,000 --> 0:17:16,000
So if one looks at the statements

428
0:17:16.26,000 --> 0:17:18,000
that have been made about this,

429
0:17:18.26,000 --> 0:17:2,000
I am impressed that when Hillary Clinton

430
0:17:20.26,000 --> 0:17:22,000
described the foreign policy

431
0:17:22.26,000 --> 0:17:24,000
of the Obama administration,

432
0:17:24.26,000 --> 0:17:27,000
she said that the foreign policy of the Obama administration

433
0:17:27.26,000 --> 0:17:3,000
was going to be smart power,

434
0:17:30.26,000 --> 0:17:32,000
as she put it, "using all the tools

435
0:17:32.26,000 --> 0:17:35,000
in our foreign policy tool box."

436
0:17:36.26,000 --> 0:17:38,000
And if we're going to deal

437
0:17:38.26,000 --> 0:17:41,000
with these two great power shifts that I've described,

438
0:17:41.26,000 --> 0:17:44,000
the power shift represented by transition among states,

439
0:17:44.26,000 --> 0:17:46,000
the power shift represented

440
0:17:46.26,000 --> 0:17:49,000
by diffusion of power away from all states,

441
0:17:49.26,000 --> 0:17:52,000
we're going to have to develop a new narrative of power

442
0:17:52.26,000 --> 0:17:55,000
in which we combine hard and soft power

443
0:17:55.26,000 --> 0:17:58,000
into strategies of smart power.

444
0:17:58.26,000 --> 0:18:01,000
And that's the good news I have. We can do that.

445
0:18:01.26,000 --> 0:18:03,000
Thank you very much.

446
0:18:03.26,000 --> 0:18:09,000
(Applause)

